message.content:
{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Lee Anderson",
            "rewritten_speech": "So, what’s being done to stop all these illegal boats crossing the Channel? 🚤"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "Firstly, I just want to acknowledge the serious incident in Southport. Thoughts are with the families affected. We’re in touch with local police and authorities to offer support. Now, about these boat crossings—they’re super risky and a real security issue. Criminal gangs are making money off people’s lives, so we’re starting a border security command with more police involvement, along with some new powers to tackle this."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Lee Anderson",
            "rewritten_speech": "Six boats came across last Saturday, and now there’s talk of four more today. That’s over 500 illegal migrants coming in, escorted by the French! Shouldn’t we stop paying the French until they cut it out?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "Yep, these boat trips are super risky. A woman tragically died just yesterday. Gangs are cramming folks onto boats to make more dough. That's why we need the new security command to crack down on these gangs hard. We’ve got to collab with not just French police but all over Europe to stop these boats from even setting sail."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Chris Murray",
            "rewritten_speech": "To sort out the border issue, we've got to work with our neighbours! What’s the plan to buddy up with France and Belgium? 🇫🇷 🇧🇪"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "You're spot on! We need to do more to cut down on these gangs. We’ve boosted our presence in Europol and got teams targeting these criminals. We’re in talks with leaders in France, Italy, and others to up our game because these gangs walk away scot-free, and people’s lives are on the line."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Lindsay Hoyle",
            "rewritten_speech": "Alright, let’s hear from the shadow Minister next."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Thomas Tugendhat",
            "rewritten_speech": "Just want to say we’re standing in solidarity with the Home Secretary about the Southport incident, and respect to Merseyside police. Now, about this migrant return deal with Europe: aren’t some of these folks potentially a security risk? Can we ensure there are tough checks so we don’t let anyone dangerous into the UK?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "Security checks are totally essential for anyone entering the UK. But these boat crossings bypass those checks, which is a big problem. We’re boosting border security with a new command and counter-terror laws. Returns of failed asylum seekers have seriously dropped since Labour was last in charge, so we need to fix that and ramp things up."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Josh Fenton-Glynn",
            "rewritten_speech": "Has anyone checked if the police are doing a good enough job dealing with violence against women and girls?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Christine Jardine",
            "rewritten_speech": "What's the plan for stopping violence against women and girls? 💪"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "For way too long, people have seen violence against women and girls as just something that happens, instead of a big emergency. We want to cut it in half by the next ten years, and it starts by making sure the police and justice system get their act together."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "Totally with you on this mission! 🚀 The Deputy Mayor of West Yorkshire is doing great stuff when it comes to getting the police to be more understanding and supportive when dealing with victims. It's key for improving victim experience."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Christine Jardine",
            "rewritten_speech": "Great to hear some action is coming, especially since the police report says 1 in 12 women face violence from a guy. But fixing this needs more than just better policing - it's got to be about changing society and dealing with misogyny from all angles, not just the violent parts."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "Absolutely, it's a huge mission. The solution isn't just up to the government. We've got to tackle toxic behaviour and work with society as a whole, including schools."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Alison Hume",
            "rewritten_speech": "Love that we're taking steps on this important mission. But my town, Scarborough, has high domestic abuse rates and no women’s refuge yet due to rising costs. 😞 How can we tackle the funding shortfall to build these vital services?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "Spot on! Refuges are vital but funding has been tough for local services. We want to support areas with high abuse rates and make every pound count for women and girls facing violence. The Chancellor will address funding soon, hopefully helping resolve this."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Elsie Blundell",
            "rewritten_speech": "After some terrible abuse cases, my area still hurts. It's not just 'grooming gangs'; abuse happens everywhere, even online. How will the new government target abusers and prevent this from happening again?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "You’re right. We need strong support and justice for victims while going after dangerous perpetrators. A new focus will be on making police pursue offenders more aggressively to keep folks safe. 🛡️"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Jessica Asato",
            "rewritten_speech": "Specialist charities are struggling hard, with some even closing due to funding issues. Can we hope that the new mission will include sorting out funding for these life-saving services?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "Absolutely. We need comprehensive partnerships everywhere, not just government work. Team up with voluntary groups to improve prevention, victim support, and offender pursuit!"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Catherine Atkinson",
            "rewritten_speech": "In Derby, violence against women and girls made up 20% of all crimes last year! We've got £83,000 for more CCTV, but what more can be done so women actually feel safe in city centres?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "True, we need more than just cameras. It's time for neighbourhood policing to make a comeback. We lost 10,000 local officers, and we need them back to make people feel safe out there."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Tracy Gilbert",
            "rewritten_speech": "How're we gonna make sure these targets are met across all parts of the UK?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "Exactly! Let's make sure we're all on the same page throughout the UK. We need to learn from each other and work together to keep women safe everywhere."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Munira Wilson",
            "rewritten_speech": "In Twickenham, we’re remembering a tragic murder from 20 years ago, and folks are worried nothing's changed. In a student survey, 69% of boys wouldn't step in to stop harassment. Can we please start teaching boys from a young age what’s the right way to act?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "Yes, it’s crucial to start young. The Education Secretary is committed to teaching this early on. We can't let these awful events keep happening without change. Let's seize this chance to improve things together."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Jim Shannon",
            "rewritten_speech": "Research says a shocking 98% of women in Northern Ireland face abuse. What talks will happen to address such high levels of violence?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "You're right—it’s not just one area’s problem. It’s everywhere. Working with all regions is vital so we don’t keep making the same mistakes over and over again. Let's ensure things genuinely change."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "James Cleverly",
            "rewritten_speech": "Welcome to your role! I'm proud of boosting arrests and charge rates for these crimes but there’s under-reporting. Make sure this doesn’t stop folks from coming forward. How will we measure the success of halving these crimes?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Yvette Cooper",
            "rewritten_speech": "Great point – it’s not just about reports. We want to know how common violence is and increase reporting where it’s been low. Charge rates have gone up, but they’re still tiny numbers━more prosecutions are needed. Let’s take a real honest look at this together."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Lindsay Hoyle",
            "rewritten_speech": "Hey everyone! Just a heads up that you can go vote for the Deputy Speakers in Committee Room 8 right now. You've got until 1:30 pm to cast your vote 🗳️. Fingers crossed, I'll be sharing the results with you all later today. Stay tuned!"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Alice Macdonald",
            "rewritten_speech": "What’s your take on the NHS dental contracting framework’s effectiveness?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Lewis Atkinson",
            "rewritten_speech": "Can you tell us how the NHS dental contracting framework is working?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Jonathan Pearce",
            "rewritten_speech": "I'd like to know your thoughts on the NHS dental contract's effectiveness."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Wes Streeting",
            "rewritten_speech": "Hey everyone, it's great to be here and even better to have my friend Alice in Norwich North with us! Being appointed as the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care is a massive deal, especially with the NHS going through a rough patch. Did you know 13 million people in England can't get the NHS dental treatment they need? 😬 That’s 28% of folks! Kids as young as 5 are ending up in hospital because of tooth decay – tragic! 😢 After my campaign promise, I’ve already started working with the British Dental Association to shake things up with the dental contract. Ready to dive in and sort it out!"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Alice Macdonald",
            "rewritten_speech": "Congratulations on the new gig! 🎉 Norfolk is a dental desert, literally! We need more dentists. UEA's got plans for a dental school. Can we meet up with reps from Norfolk and UEA about this?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Wes Streeting",
            "rewritten_speech": "Norfolk’s dental situation is shocking, only 36 dentists per 100k people compared to 53 nationally! Yep, it's the Sahara of dental deserts. 🌵 I'm already on it with the UEA's dental school proposal, and I’m more than happy to get together to chat about this!"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Lewis Atkinson",
            "rewritten_speech": "People in Sunderland Central can't get routine NHS dental care, and emergencies are just as bad. What are your plans beyond contract reform to make sure urgent dental services are local?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Wes Streeting",
            "rewritten_speech": "Thanks, Lewis! Yes, urgent action is needed alongside contract changes: 700k more urgent dental appointments are coming, with dentists ready to help ASAP. We’re speeding things up with the BDA and will keep updating everyone. 👍"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Jonathan Pearce",
            "rewritten_speech": "High Peak is in need of some serious dental help too. Elderly folks can’t eat properly because they can’t get dentures sorted. What’s the plan to undo 14 years of dental NHS mess?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Wes Streeting",
            "rewritten_speech": "Good to see you, Jonathan! It’ll take time to fix the 14-year mess, but starting with those 700k urgent appointments and contract reforms is a solid start. We've got the backs of all communities, especially rural ones like yours. 🛠️"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Harriett Baldwin",
            "rewritten_speech": "How’s the dental recovery plan doing, particularly regarding more NHS dental appointments in Worcs and Herefordshire?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Wes Streeting",
            "rewritten_speech": "During the election, people made clear they weren’t happy with the previous plan—NHS dentistry is practically missing in huge areas. We’re keeping the good bits and scrapping the rest for a serious contract reform. It's about time, considering the broken promises since 2010! 😡"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Layla Moran",
            "rewritten_speech": "A year without a dentist?! One of my constituents can't eat or sleep due to painful abscesses. 😖 The BDA fears more delays due to the NHS review. Can you give us a timeline for changes?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Wes Streeting",
            "rewritten_speech": "Cheers, Layla! The previous government’s inaction is affecting lives. Bevan gave people dignity with NHS Dentistry—it’s disgraceful that folks are suffering now. Lord Darzi’s NHS review comes out in September, but we’re already working to get those 700k appointments going. Keeping you in the loop! 📅"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Joe Robertson",
            "rewritten_speech": "In places like the Isle of Wight, dentists are scarce! Will you stick to the plan for 240 'golden hellos' for new dentists by year’s end?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Wes Streeting",
            "rewritten_speech": "Congrats and welcome, Joe! It's vital to get more dentists into places like yours. 🤝 We're exploring ways to encourage dentists to do more NHS work and move to where they’re needed most. Yep, those incentives for new dentists are on the table."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Lindsay Hoyle",
            "rewritten_speech": "Let's hear from the shadow Minister."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Saqib Bhatti",
            "rewritten_speech": "Congrats on the new role! Victoria Atkins was all about improving access to care, including dentistry. Under her, we planned dental vans for rural and coastal England by this autumn. So, will those dental vans be ready soon?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Wes Streeting",
            "rewritten_speech": "Seriously? After 14 years, all they’ve got to brag about are dental vans? 😩 The last government missed too many chances to fix NHS dentistry. While the shadow Minister had a front-row seat watching repeated failures, we’re shifting gears for real solutions. It’s about time!"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Steffan Aquarone",
            "rewritten_speech": "What are you guys planning to do to make it easier for us to see an NHS dentist?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Stephen Kinnock",
            "rewritten_speech": "Thanks for the question and welcome to the team. Because of what the Conservatives have done over the past 14 years, a jaw-dropping 13 million folks can't get a dentist appointment. I know your area has it extra tough with the fewest dentists per person in the whole country. 💔 Our plan will add 700,000 more urgent dental appointments and bring dentists to places that really need them. We're thinking long-term too and will change the dental contract to make things better."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Steffan Aquarone",
            "rewritten_speech": "Exactly! In North Norfolk, we've had the leftover dental treatment resources shifted elsewhere. And now the local health board has to send this year’s unused funds back to the Treasury? 🙄 Can you at least promise to keep our dental funds safe here?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Stephen Kinnock",
            "rewritten_speech": "Right, as the Health Secretary mentioned, they've already met with the British Dental Association to talk about fixing the NHS dental contract long-term. 🎙️ This includes sorting out what's called 'units of dental activity' and we need to get cracking on those talks. But let's be clear, the Conservatives really let the NHS contract fall apart over the years, almost pushing dentistry services over the edge."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Claire Hazelgrove",
            "rewritten_speech": "Big congrats to the Health Secretary and the awesome new team in Government! 👏 Thanks for standing up for folks in my area who struggle to access dental care. How are you going to link together essential services like housing and dental care? As we plan to build 1.5 million new homes, we’ve got to make sure we don’t create more areas with no dental services. How will you work with other departments to sort this out?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Stephen Kinnock",
            "rewritten_speech": "Cheers for the question and congrats on your election! Our dental rescue plan focuses on getting 700,000 more appointments by generating extra funds. We're going after tax evaders and closing loopholes to make this happen. 💰 We're also tempting new dentists to come work where they're needed most with 'golden hello' bonuses. Plus, we’re working on things like supervised toothbrushing for little ones aged 3 to 5, 'cause it's always better to prevent issues than fix them later."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Lindsay Hoyle",
            "rewritten_speech": "Alright everyone, before we kick off today, let's give a massive shoutout to John Tamlyn, our Bar Doorkeeper, who’s hanging up his hat today after an amazing 36-year run! 🎉 John started his journey here back in '88, first helping out at the Sergeant at Arms office, and then leading the Speaker’s procession to the Chamber for the past 26 years. He's the guy you went to for all things Chamber – basically the Wikipedia of House procedures. 📚 Some might say he shared a bit too much info at times! 🤣\n\nEveryone in the team and beyond knows him as one of the sharpest-dressed folks around, with a cracking sense of humour. He's got a serious thing for music, especially '70s disco and '80s pop, and I've heard he's got some killer dance moves. 💃 Also, he's quite the photographer! 📸 Let’s all join in and thank John for his loyal service and wish him a super happy retirement. Cheers, John! 🍾"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Hon. Members",
            "rewritten_speech": "Absolutely! 👏"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Debbie Abrahams",
            "rewritten_speech": "What are you doing to help make a lasting ceasefire happen in Gaza?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "David Lammy",
            "rewritten_speech": "Just a couple of weeks into the job, I went over to Israel and the West Bank and was the first to really push for a ceasefire, unlike those before me. I met with the leaders there and pressed them for an immediate stop to the fighting. Plus, I laid out the need for a real and lasting path towards a two-state solution."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Debbie Abrahams",
            "rewritten_speech": "Glad to have you and the team on board! Thanks for pushing for the ceasefire during your Israel visit; my local community really felt its impact. Don't you think a permanent ceasefire is super important for the people in Gaza and it would also calm things down in the Middle East? Considering the attacks on the Golan Heights, things heating up between Hezbollah and Israel, and even the Houthis getting involved, we really need it."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "David Lammy",
            "rewritten_speech": "You're spot on! The suffering in Gaza is just too much to take. The war's gotta end pronto. Also, with things heating up in the region, going with Biden's plan would help cool things off. For a better life in Gaza and around there, it's crucial to go for that plan right now. ✌️"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Tom Gordon",
            "rewritten_speech": "Hey, what chats have you had with the Iranian folks about these human rights issues going on over there?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Hamish Falconer",
            "rewritten_speech": "The way Iran is treating women, girls, minorities, and anyone standing up for human rights is just not on. 😡 We're teaming up with other countries to call them out and we'll be bringing it up at the UN Third Committee later this year."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Tom Gordon",
            "rewritten_speech": "The Iranian government is really going after the BBC Persian team and their families, trying to scare them into quitting journalism. Press freedom is important everywhere. So, will the Foreign Secretary work with the Culture Secretary to maybe rethink the funding cuts to BBC Persian and even boost support for their work?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Hamish Falconer",
            "rewritten_speech": "Great question! Iran is definitely not an easy place for journalists—they face all sorts of trouble like being harassed and unfairly locked up. We're going to bring this up with Iran's new government as soon as they're in place. 📅 For now, the Foreign Office funds a quarter of the BBC World Service's budget, and we'll be looking into that budget soon."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Dan Tomlinson",
            "rewritten_speech": "Welcome, Minister! We sadly saw this weekend that the IRGC is up to no good, spreading chaos by supporting groups like Hamas and Hezbollah. Can you update us on banning the IRGC, something the Conservatives didn’t do before? And can you reassure us that the UK still firmly backs Israel against these threats?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Hamish Falconer",
            "rewritten_speech": "The IRGC is definitely a threat, and we're ready to take action wherever they cause trouble. We review our list of terrorist organisations carefully, but I can't say right now if we're considering adding any new ones. Iran is still stirring things up in the Middle East with its allies, and we'll work with others internationally to push back against that."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Lindsay Hoyle",
            "rewritten_speech": "Hey everyone, just a quick update! 🎉 The King has officially given his thumbs-up to the *Supply and Appropriation (Main Estimates) Act 2024*. So yeah, it's a done deal now! 👍"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Andrew Jones",
            "rewritten_speech": "How's it going with getting more women and girls involved in sports?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Lucy Frazer",
            "rewritten_speech": "Women and girls should have the same chances as blokes in sports. We're putting £600 million towards making sports accessible for everyone. Plus, we're dropping £30 million into the Lionesses Futures Fund to set up 30 new pitches that give priority to women and girls, with chances for 8,000 of them to get involved. ⚽️"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Andrew Jones",
            "rewritten_speech": "The Lionesses have done awesome, especially Rachel Daly from Harrogate! But what's being done to support smaller sports so that girls have a lively grassroots scene to thrive in?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Lucy Frazer",
            "rewritten_speech": "Rachel absolutely smashed it, being last year's top scorer in the women's super league! 😁 We are pushing for sports at all levels. Sport England has this fab 'This Girl Can' campaign that helps millions of women and girls join sports. The School Games programme is urging kids to get sporty too. 🎽"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Lindsay Hoyle",
            "rewritten_speech": "Let's hear from the shadow Secretary of State."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Thangam Debbonaire",
            "rewritten_speech": "Lately, there’s been some shocking sexist rubbish thrown at sportswomen who are just being brilliant. Kudos to Stuart Andrew for standing up against the nastiness. Misogynistic junk is really dangerous and it’s turning women and girls off sports. Does the Secretary of State think every sports body should have a plan to wipe out sexism and abuse?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Lucy Frazer",
            "rewritten_speech": "Totally agree that we can't have bullying or sexism in sports. No-go. Every sporting body needs to check what they're doing. We've outlined in our sports strategy to ensure fair competition and integrity. 💪"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Thangam Debbonaire",
            "rewritten_speech": "Talking about the Carney review, the Government’s dragging its feet on women's football, with no clear plan on how they're gonna implement the recommendations. Without strong leadership, all the efforts could go down the drain. Players, fans, and clubs all deserve swift action from the top. Will the Secretary of State chair the implementation group and update Parliament about it?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Lucy Frazer",
            "rewritten_speech": "I disagree with your point. We’re all in on boosting women in sports and football. I've chatted with Karen Carney many times—her report's top-notch. We back its recommendations, lots of which the FA needs to sort out. I’m making sure things get done. All the sports bodies are on the implementation board, meeting in March, and I'll keep tabs on it closely."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Lindsay Hoyle",
            "rewritten_speech": "Hey everybody! Just a heads up, the Annunciator system, which flashes up info, is running slow today. 🐢 You'll see a bit of a delay when it updates stuff. The Clerk is already on it, fixing things up as we speak with some tech magic! ⚡️"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Adam Jogee",
            "rewritten_speech": "Hey, had any chats lately with Northern Ireland's First Minister and deputy First Minister? 🗨️"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Hilary Benn",
            "rewritten_speech": "Lovely to see everyone so engaged with Northern Ireland stuff! Big shoutout to our newly elected peeps over there. I've met up with the First Minister and Deputy First Minister twice in my first few days—had some good chats about lots of things, especially our plan to ditch and replace this legacy law that's got no fans around. I'll clue you all in on our plans soon! 📢"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Adam Jogee",
            "rewritten_speech": "Awesome to see my friends Colum and Claire here! 🎉 I reckon folks in both Newcastle-under-Lyme and Northern Ireland will be quite pleased with the Secretary's promise to scrap that legacy law, 'cause it's not been popular at all. Can you promise to ask loads of people for their thoughts on it and keep us posted?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Hilary Benn",
            "rewritten_speech": "Yep, I promise! 🕊️ The legacy law's really unpopular in Northern Ireland—none of the parties or victim's families are into it. We're definitely going to chat with loads of people about how to change it. We want everyone, or at least most, to be on board with whatever we do next!"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Robin Swann",
            "rewritten_speech": "Thank you for the info. 😊 There are loads of parties in Northern Ireland, not just the ones led by the First and Deputy First Minister. Will you make sure to chat openly with all of them?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Hilary Benn",
            "rewritten_speech": "Absolutely, I promise that too! I’ve met with all the party leaders, and just like I told my mate Adam, we’re going to involve all the Northern Ireland parties in our decisions. 🗣️"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Lindsay Hoyle",
            "rewritten_speech": "Time for the shadow Secretary of State to jump in! 🎤"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Alex Burghart",
            "rewritten_speech": "Big congrats on your new gig! 🤝 I know you'll be ace, and I can’t wait to team up for everyone in Northern Ireland. Also, a shoutout to your predecessor—he's definitely missed by his crew. Can you promise to be a strong supporter of the Union while you’re in charge?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Hilary Benn",
            "rewritten_speech": "Thanks, mate! 🎉 Let's collaborate and keep the Union strong—it's something the Government is super committed to, as we said in our manifesto!"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Alex Burghart",
            "rewritten_speech": "Cheers for your answer. The Government’s on about doing the Windsor Framework right, but the manifestos never mentioned the Command Paper, which was a big deal for getting Stormont back on track. It’s got ideas to boost the Union like the East-West Council and InterTrade UK. Can you make sure to go through with those bits that make the Union stronger?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Hilary Benn",
            "rewritten_speech": "Sure thing. As you know, we backed some instruments and the Humble Address when we were in opposition. We’re setting up a panel to keep an eye on things, and we've had a win with the EU on dental amalgam—a 10-year break, loads of cheers from Northern Ireland parties for that! 🎉🦷"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Sammy Wilson",
            "rewritten_speech": "Has anyone chatted with the other gov folks about fixing up Casement Park? 🤔"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Claire Hanna",
            "rewritten_speech": "Have there been any money talks with the finance head about doing up Casement Park?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Jim Allister",
            "rewritten_speech": "So, how much cash is the government planning to put towards the Casement Park makeover?"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Hilary Benn",
