{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Oliver Heald",
            "rewritten_speech": "Alright folks, I'm here to get this Bill read for the second time. I kicked this off with a quick ten-minute Bill last June, but it didn’t get picked up last session, so let's give it another go! It's gained a bunch of support from all around, especially some big names in the House. The Bill aims to push the Secretary of State to report on giving financial help to parents whose kids are stuck in hospital for ages. Big shoutout to the Ministers who've been keen to chat about it, especially my mate Jo Churchill who's got personal experience on this kind of stuff. \n\nThis all started when Ceri Menai-Davis, one of my constituents, got in touch after his son Hugh, just six, passed away from a rare cancer. Ceri and his wife Frances, who are here today, went through hell, visiting the hospital daily to be with their son as he went from a sporty kid to leaving us. They’ve set up a charity, **It’s Never You**, to help other parents going through this trauma, offering mental and physical support, and they're looking for some financial help as well.\n\nThe numbers aren't huge—around 4,000 kids a year spend over two months in hospital. These parents are footing daily visits or staying over and incurring loads of costs. Ceri asked if I'd help them meet a Health Minister to talk better support for parents, and I got them in the room with Edward Argar, the then Minister of State. We walked him through all the practical issues, like getting food on weekends and mental support. He was pretty helpful and is tying this into the new children's hospitals that are being planned.\n\nCeri’s charity links parents of sick kids to a supportive community and provides info via a blog and app, not handled by the authorities. They’re also handing out well-being bags in hospitals across the UK. And oh! A shoutout to Addenbrooke’s Hospital in Cambridge, our local, which is working on a mega new children's hospital project, binding mental and physical health together.\n\nIn October, the new hospital plans went a step forward. It's about delivering top research mixed with medical care. Provisions like specialist wards and up-to-date treatment technology putting kids and families front and centre. Hats off to Matt Hancock for approving it. Ceri’s insights have been great to the planning team over there.\n\nBeyond the money side, we need better cancer care. Back in November 2021, I spoke about little Jessica Brady's case, who also left us due to a misdiagnosed rare cancer. We pressed the Government, delivering a petition with 213,000 signatures. There's a strong push to catch cancers early and bust diagnostic delays. Loads going on with rapid diagnostic centres and integrated care boards.\n\nCeri's financial worries highlight what many parents face. They end up losing jobs to be with their kids. We've been chatting to Work and Pensions and Health departments about this. There's some help like unpaid leave and universal credit adjustments, but more is definitely needed.\n\nThrough this Bill, I am asking for a proper report about possible financial aid for such parents. I want government to dive into the current policies, see how extra help could improve things, and involve various groups in consults to frame a holistic approach.\n\nThis could be Hugh’s legacy, helping others facing the same fate. Let’s call it “Hugh’s Report”."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Jo Gideon",
            "rewritten_speech": "Agree 100%! Instead of just being crushed by their tragedy, Ceri and Frances did something incredible by starting a charity. The kind of determination they have is amazing, and all parents campaigning for change, like Stacy who fought for Harper-Lee’s Law after her daughter died from swallowing a button battery, deserve massive respect. Without them, we MPs couldn't get things done! 🎤👏"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Oliver Heald",
            "rewritten_speech": "Spot on! Despite their loss, Ceri and Frances started a charity that’s really making a difference. With Edward Argar, we’re developing long-term strategies for early cancer diagnosis, including for rare ones like Jessica's case. The goal? Catch three-quarters of cancers early so 55,000 more people can survive them five years longer. Rapid diagnostic centres, new hospital services, and a focus on all ages and types of cancer are keys to a brighter future. \n\nBut let's talk finances: Parents with kids in hospital are often losing jobs to be there for their kids. Additional support could change lives, but current financial aid is a patchwork. This Bill wants to take it further, assess the system fully, and see how some extra support could positively impact parents and kids. Many charities, including those like Ceri’s and Young Lives vs Cancer, have already flagged challenges like delayed NHS travel support. \n\nI’d love to see those in charge directly speaking with parents like the Menai-Davis’s. Making sure these parents can just focus on their child's well-being, without the mental burden of money worries, would do wonders for them. So, yeah, let’s push this forward!"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Vicky Foxcroft",
            "rewritten_speech": "Big props to Sir Oliver Heald for laying down such a strong case. I won't keep you long cos we all want to hear what the Minister has to say. Labour is fully backing this Bill."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Jo Churchill",
            "rewritten_speech": "Thanks to everyone involved, especially Sir Oliver Heald. Ceri and Frances started the charity **It’s Never You** after losing their son. Experience like that is a game-changer. \n\nI’ve been there, having had cancer multiple times, and I know how it flips everything upside-down. Your world revolves around hospital visits, hoping for answers and miracles. We must support parents more effectively and join forces to make the practical and emotional journey of having a sick kid easier.\n\nThere are already some aids like universal credit, carer’s allowance, and disability addition, but we know more can be done. Our commitment is to set up a stakeholder forum and consult parents, professionals, charities—you name it—to build solid proposals. Let’s meet soon, Ceri and Frances, to lead these consultations.\n\nWe need those voices to shape future decisions, and this process will be quicker than trying to legislate it. Let's respect that dedication and bring purpose to their pain."
