        },
        {
            "speakername": "Vicky Ford",
            "rewritten_speech": "Thanks for bringing this up, Philip. The Children's Commissioner did some accurate research showing how even small attendance changes impact outcomes. Since COVID, attendance has been a concern among teachers. There are many reasons for increased absence, like anxiety, unmet special education needs, and even parents keeping kids home for minor sicknesses post-pandemic. For vulnerable kids, regular school is protective. An expert told me that attendance at alternative provisions is now below 60%. That's worrying as regular absence can expose kids to things like crime. A roundtable of experts I attended completely supported the Bill and shared insights on why absences are rising—economic issues, relocation due to housing, and more. Interestingly, some ethnic groups with high levels of English as a second language have better attendance compared to others. Girls' attendance, especially in years 8-10, is falling due to lower self-esteem and mental well-being issues. The Government's online safety work is crucial here. 🌐 COVID broke the unwritten bond between schools and families, and even teacher strikes may have added to the problem. Anecdotally, parents working from home find it challenging to get kids to school sometimes. The Bill aims to make the current non-mandatory school guidance mandatory, like having an attendance champion at every school. It'll make sure that the support doesn't vary depending on your postcode. It's not a catch-all, but it's a strong step to make sure that we give school attendance the priority it deserves. It's backed by heaps of experts and research from places like the Centre for Social Justice. Let's work together to make sure kids are where they should be—in school. 🚸"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Philip Dunne",
            "rewritten_speech": "I’m totally on board with this Bill, especially considering COVID's lasting effects. School absences have seriously affected kids' social skills, like going from primary to secondary school. Being around other kids is crucial for social development. This Bill is well-timed because lots of kids are still dealing with pandemic-related issues. On a related note, mental health associations suggested a special absence code for mental health issues. With mental health support teams rolling out in schools, hopefully, the Minister can say more about that. Lastly, making schools publish their attendance policies will be a game-changer. It'll help teachers explain the importance of knowing the policy before picking what secondary school to attend. It gives schools a way to show parents that attending school is a must. I back this Bill 100%! 🎒"
