        {
            "speakername": "Nicola Richards",
            "rewritten_speech": "Hey, it's a big deal speaking after so many thoughtful peeps like Steve McCabe. Big thanks 🎉 for looking out for the Jewish community in Birmingham and standing by Israel. It's hard for me to wrap my head around how immense the Holocaust was, you know? Every time you hear a story from someone who lived it, you get a glimpse, but it's just the tip of the iceberg. Each person's story is unique, shaped by where they were born or even where they tried to hide when things got intense in Europe. We hear about those who watched loved ones die or made snap decisions that saved them or others.\n\nThe Holocaust wasn't just a number—6 million Jewish lives snuffed out—it was a whole world of dreams and futures just gone. Fast forward to 7 October, it was the deadliest day for Jewish people since WWII. Met folks who've lost, like this brave 23-year-old who told us she lost 60 mates in one day! 😢 Just can't imagine that kind of loss.\n\nI wish I didn't have to compare anything to the Holocaust. There's no comparison. We have Israel now so this stuff doesn't ever happen again. But 7 October was serious, friends. Got to see the aftermath first-hand in Israel. Saw a display by survivors of the Nova festival, and it was honestly heartbreaking. Tables of shoes and clothes from folks who just came to dance 🎶 And it hit me right in the feels thinking of the heaps of shoes I saw at Auschwitz. Those were young women, just like me, who just went there to dance. It's chilling!\n\nWe say 'never again', but looking at antisemitism today and hearing some folks outright deny that anything happened on 7 October, it's shocking. This denial isn't just misunderstanding; it's a stubborn refusal to face facts, kind of like Holocaust denial. We all need to be more vocal against this hate so nothing like this ever gets close to happening again. Let's keep educating ourselves and others about the past."
