        },
        {
            "speakername": "Theresa Villiers",
            "rewritten_speech": "Gosh, following those speeches feels like a lot, but here goes. Every year when I think about the Holocaust, it boggles my mind how such an advanced German society fell into this barbarism. Those Jewish communities were around for centuries, and it took intense Nazi propaganda to make their own neighbours turn away when Jews were sent on trains to the camps.\n\nHolocaust Memorial Day is also about remembering other genocides, like the Holodomor in Ukraine. Still, the sheer scale of the Nazi atrocities—killing six million Jews and others who were targeted just for being different—is hard to grasp. But let's not forget the heroes who helped, risking it all. \n\nWe should also reflect on historical mistakes, like Britain's reluctance to help Jewish refugees in the 1930s during its Mandate in Palestine. Different decisions could have saved many lives.\n\nWith antisemitism on the rise, it's so important to remind younger folks what it leads to. Visiting Yad Vashem in Jerusalem or the Nova exhibition in Tel Aviv provides deep, unsettling reminders. And seeing the 7 October footage literally haunts my sleep 💔. Let's learn from this, as Chief Rabbi Ephraim Mirvis points out, throwing around words like 'genocide' misleads and insults true victims. Saying 'never again' means facing hate vigilantly. Let’s do better, now more than ever."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Matthew Offord",
            "rewritten_speech": "Wow, I've been attending Holocaust Memorial events for 22 years now. I wondered if we'd run out of things to say, yet sadly, this topic feels ever more urgent. Back in the early 2000s, antisemitism didn't feel as pervasive as it does today. \n\nThrough reading works like 'Maus' by Art Spiegelman, I learned a lot about the Holocaust. But Uris’s 'Exodus' talks about the tough situation many Jewish survivors faced, including the failure of the UK and other countries to accept them right after WWII. This made the case for Israel's statehood even stronger, considering Jewish populations had few places to go.\n\nNow, antisemitism isn't just stories from the past—it's alive today. Young folks in my area sometimes face hostility simply for being Jewish. I've even dealt with incidents personally. Not long ago, 7 October felt personal too, with attacks in Israel—I met Nathanel Young early in his life before he tragically died.\n\nToday’s antisemitism isn’t just out there—it's local, too. A recent email from a Jewish mum told me about her son being scared to even say Jewish words in public. That's concerning! Kids shouldn't hide their identity; freedom's for everyone, just as Chief Rabbi Mirvis urges we remember."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Kirsten Oswald",
            "rewritten_speech": "I'm really glad to be part of this debate, especially since my community marks Holocaust Memorial Day in a meaningful way. We get to hear incredibly brave and poignant personal stories. For instance, young folks like Kaela-Kaliza Molina talked about the Rwandan genocide powerfully. And others, like Geraldine Shenkin, shared heart-wrenching stories of relatives like her mum Marianne Grant, who survived unimaginable horrors in camps like Auschwitz.\n\nImportantly, the theme of ‘fragility of freedom’ feels very real. And while we need more patience and understanding generally, this theme truly exposes how thin and delicate freedom can be. It’s apparent worldwide and here at home, as we see spikes in antisemitism and Islamophobia. Staying vigilant could help us stop other deep-seated prejudices from boiling over.\n\nLocally, our youth are amazing—they're spearheading these remembrance activities! And such lessons are crucial. Plus, we must see hope and potential around us. People like Henry Wuga and Jane Haining show us courage and sacrifice through their examples. Let's remember these lessons and keep working towards a future where everyone enjoys, and isn't afraid of freedom."
