{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Margaret Hodge",
            "rewritten_speech": "I want to talk about Holocaust Memorial Day. Big thanks to some MPs for pushing this debate, even if they're not here right now. Also, massive shoutout to the Holocaust Memorial Day Trust and the Holocaust Educational Trust. 🌟 Without their effort, we wouldn't be able to remember the horrors of the Holocaust or other genocides, like those in Rwanda and Bosnia. \n\nThis is pretty special for me because it’s my last time speaking in this debate. It's a rough time to bring it up, though. I just got back from Israel, where I visited a kibbutz called Kfar Azar. It's a place where people wanted peace with Gaza. But on 7 October, a lot of them were killed, and others have been captured. Those who survived went through immense cruelty and fear for their future, kinda like what happened during the Holocaust. In Gaza and Israel, people are scared, facing trauma and terror from bombardments and lack of aid. \n\nAs we remember the Holocaust, it’s frustrating to think, 'Has the world really learned anything?' This year, we’re focusing on how fragile freedom is. That theme is crucial—it allows us to see how our freedom can easily be lost and how we need to protect others who flee persecution now.\n\nThis hits home for me because of my family's history. We lost relatives in the Holocaust, like my grandmother and uncle. Other family members got out just days before the war and went through hell. My granddad came to England in 1939 and wrote a diary that gives us a glimpse into those times. In it, he mentioned things like antisemitism here in the UK and being treated as an 'enemy alien'. It showed how fragile freedom was back then, and kinda still is today.\n\nFast forward to me. I came to the UK from Egypt stateless in 1949. My dad had some nasty encounters with antisemitism back home, so we left. After applying for British nationality, we went through some pretty intense questioning, which made my freedom feel really fragile. \n\nSo what's the takeaway? Freedom is never guaranteed, and it’s essential to treat those escaping persecution with respect. We can't blame asylum seekers or use language that scares people. We need to stand firmly against genocide and remember that our efforts have to mean something. Let's make sure 'Never again' isn’t just something we say, but something we actually live by."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Jim Shannon",
            "rewritten_speech": "Great job bringing up this debate. Most of us really back Israel. Remembering the Holocaust isn’t about dwelling on horrors; it’s about making sure everyone, regardless of faith, learns from it so something that horrible never happens again."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Margaret Hodge",
            "rewritten_speech": "Totally agree with you. We're not always as great as we pretend to be. My granddad and I both felt unwelcome when we came here. Today’s refugees face this kind of hostile environment too, thanks to some politicians vilifying them. Let’s think hard about how we talk and act before we judge past atrocities. The rules and practices today, designed to exclude asylum seekers, matter—and so do the fees for visas and the refusal to let them work.\n\nThe hostility faced by my granddad echoes today. We must be responsible and confront genocide wherever it shows its ugly face. If we ignore these unfolding situations, the horrors my family faced will mean nothing. Freedom should be a true value we pass down to future generations with integrity."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Rosie Winterton",
            "rewritten_speech": "Let's hear from the Father of the House."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Peter Bottomley",
            "rewritten_speech": "Sorry I missed the start of your speech, Margaret. I was trying to get a transcript from a hearing about the Holocaust Memorial Bill. I’ve heard from actual Holocaust survivors, which was super moving. We lit candles for victims, including those in Darfur, which reminded me how our own actions haven’t been spotless. If Israel had existed sooner, the Holocaust death toll might’ve been lower. More Jews than we thought died back then, and many more today have connections to the event as they uncover their family history—mine too.\n\nI need to mention my cousin, who went to Bergen-Belsen to help people. We should have a proper debate about the memorial in Victoria Tower Gardens another time. Instead, visit the Holocaust Galleries at the Imperial War Museum. Hitler was influenced by defeat and extreme nationalistic ideas, which drove his rise to power.\n\nReal democracy matters—losing elections without chaos is essential. It’s sad that there are fewer truly democratic countries now than when I first ran for election. We need proper education about the Holocaust so people understand how leaders like Adolf Hitler come to power and potentially do the same. We can't have people using force to attack specific groups based on race or religion; education and being willing to lose elections without resorting to violence is crucial."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Alistair Carmichael",
            "rewritten_speech": "Thanks to the Business Committee for letting us have this debate here. It’s more powerful having this discussion in Parliament. Hats off to Margaret for her great speech, sharing her family story and giving us lessons for today.\n\nThinking of next year being 80 years since WWII ends, who'll remember? I was born a while after the war, and the info about it was everywhere in comics and books—none of that for today’s kids. The more we drift from that lived experience, the more essential these conversations and the work of groups like the Holocaust Educational Trust become.\n\nI represent Shetland, and during the war, the Shetland bus was key in helping 350 fugitives—including many Jews—escape Nazi-occupied Norway. Our debates need the context of current events; what’s happening in Israel and Gaza are tragic reminders. We must understand antisemitism still lives among us, creeping through under different forms. If left unchecked, it can grow dangerous—calling it out matters."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Bob Stewart",
            "rewritten_speech": "I've got a personal story about genocide from Bosnia early '90s. In Germany, as an infantry battalion commander, I phoned my mum from where our camp was near Bergen-Belsen. A grim spot… then Mum told me she’d been there in 1945. She was ashamed—a response to seeing the Holocaust firsthand through the SOE, having joined up to fight Nazis.\n\nI understood when I went to Bosnia—it was madness. I'd never seen such barbarity until I witnessed how Muslim Bosnians were treated. Trying to be neutral wasn’t enough; emotions ran high. Ahmici village was destroyed, and I witnessed the horror of genocide—massacres, mass graves, horrific living conditions—frustrating neutrality. I reported to the UN, and we eventually set up the International Criminal Tribunal.\n\nGenocide isn't just WWII. As Margaret said, watch out. It didn't stop; it's happened again. We need to shout, 'Never again,' loudly to prevent it as best we can."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Lyn Brown",
            "rewritten_speech": "Following Bob's moving words is tough. It's so vital we highlight what’s happening with genocides, past and present. Big thanks to groups like the Holocaust Memorial Trust for their work. I can't wrap my head around how ordinary people coldly carried out industrial-scale mass murder—like against Jewish Holocaust victims.\n\nRwanda, 30 years ago—more genocide. I want to share Daphrosa's terrifying story. Before the genocide, she lived a happy life with her family. But when hatred spread, neighbours she trusted betrayed them. Her family faced unimaginable ordeals—rape, torture, murder.\n\nHer horrific experience reminds us we must learn from these past events—Holocaust to Rwanda—and recognize they were fueled exactly by that: dehumanizing propaganda and systemic racism. Genocides happen when ordinary people make horrific choices when confronted with hatred. So many ignored cries for help back then, and 'Never again' wasn't real. Let's make sure 'never again' means something this time too."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Andrew Percy",
            "rewritten_speech": "Following Lyn, let me share my own horrifying recent experience. I saw the aftermath of the October 7 attacks in Israel—something I thought I'd never witness in my lifetime. That trip hit me hard; I'm struggling to put into words the impact—seeing and smelling the sites of Jewish murders. It's an emotional scar that will stay with me forever.\n\nWhat's shocking is watching what's happening in our streets today. Extremists, hatred against Jews, calls for violence, even at protests, feel too familiar. Extreme anti-Zionism is echoing past times when people turned a blind eye to horrors like Nazi influence.\n\nWhat do I expect from our Government? To stand firm on the real meaning of British values. To protect free speech without violence, and help everyone—whether choosing a different life path or living free of fear. These horrific events echo the past; the hatred keeps resurfacing. I'm gutted, but proud to keep speaking out."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Christine Jardine",
            "rewritten_speech": "It's a bit unsettling talking now, in a time like this. Growing up, the Holocaust felt distant, something we learned about, but also something that couldn't happen here again. But since 7 October, I worry that complacency might get the best of us. \n\nI recently chatted with uni students, and I was gobsmacked to hear antisemitic comments being tossed around. I can't grasp how these attitudes creep back in. Worse yet, Jewish communities, like those in Edinburgh, feel isolated and unheard.\n\nWe've seen ignorance around the Holocaust growing, particularly among young Americans. Antisemitism seems like a creeping danger. We must be all ears to Holocaust survivors, to truly hear their stories and experience, before complacency ignites something far more sinister within our society again."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Helen Morgan",
            "rewritten_speech": "Doesn't the answer lie in hearing Jewish people's real-life experiences up close? My local, Natalie Cumming, wrote about her family’s flight from terror, including her sister surviving Auschwitz—a tough but vital read. We need folks to engage with stories like hers to undo the prejudice."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Christine Jardine",
            "rewritten_speech": "Right on! It’s crucial; hearing survivors' voices matters so much—it was at an event in Parliament early this week. We've read surveys saying many young folks aren't even sure that the Holocaust definitely happened 👀. Awareness lacks, and antisemitism is leaking into daily life. We need to halt this drift sooner rather than later. In Israel, if you visit Yad Vashem, you’ll understand the gravity of this journey from dark to light. Let’s snap out and be vigilant; remember there's light ahead."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Paul Beresford",
            "rewritten_speech": "Absolutely stunned by what I've heard. Growing up in New Zealand, our community was multicultural but never racially charged—unlike now, where we've horrifying reminders. In my professional sphere connected to medicine and dentistry, antisemitism shocks me—it’s appalling and viscerally spreading. This must be stopped before it grows, much like before WWII. We can’t let this cycle continue; it's urgent."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Steve McCabe",
            "rewritten_speech": "Raised in a family chatting about WWII, I was late understanding the Holocaust’s impact, so thanks to Margaret for driving this debate. Auschwitz taught me its dark lesson, especially as a teacher with students. Great work by groups like March of the Living too, they're essential.\n\nI met incredible survivors. Yet recent Gaza events make me question what’s learned. Protests overlook the horrors of 7 October, confusing me with chants that feel divisive. The Nazis misled, blamed unjustly then; supporters can't do the same now.\n\nSupporting peace while genuinely addressing the suffering experienced in Gaza and Israel matters, but the inconsistencies make me wonder—what’ve we learned from those scars? We can’t afford to ignore history and let antisemitism seep into society. We learned from atrocities, why repeat them?"
        }
    ]
}

