{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Chris Elmore",
            "rewritten_speech": "Hey everyone, thanks for supporting my Bill! I wanted a law that makes a real difference to daily life for people suffering loss when I got my chance to propose something. Big thanks to groups like Gingerbread and the Fawcett Society for all their help. I'm all about cross-party teamwork, so cheers to the Minister, officials, and Rebecca Harris from Castle Point, who keeps things running smoothly for us MPs. This Bill is all about ensuring those who lose a partner, wife or mother in childbirth get the right to parental leave. It's heartbreaking stuff—imagine having to raise a newborn and plan a funeral without your partner. Many won't ever face this, but for those who do, we need to make it easier. Let's not forget about the issues with employment rights, too—many parents still miss out on shared parental leave. Around 1% of mums take it up, and only 5% of eligible employees overall. Loads find the process just too tough. And given that about 261 women die each year during or soon after pregnancy, sadly these numbers are rising. Ethnic minority women, especially those from economically poorer areas, are hit the hardest. So we need this change more than ever, especially for financially vulnerable dads who lose their partner and have no leave. Let's start opening up more discussions on employment rights. This Bill is just the beginning. Cheers, everyone, let's get this done!"
        },
