{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Gavin Robinson",
            "rewritten_speech": "I'm super excited to finally talk about this British Citizenship bill for Northern Ireland! 🎉 It's a rare chance for a backbench MP like me to do something like this, so I'm really grateful to everyone who's supported it so far. Big shoutout to all the House staff, the Home Office Minister and his team, the Government Whips, and all the MPs from Northern Ireland who got behind me. What we're trying to do here is sort out a long-standing issue about citizenship laws for people from Northern Ireland. Since the Belfast Agreement, it's been clear that people in Northern Ireland could choose to be Irish or British, but there was never a proper way to allow people born in the Republic of Ireland, who live here, to become British citizens. This Bill aims to fix that 📜. If you were born in the Republic of Ireland but have lived and worked all your life in the UK, you should be able to become a British citizen no problem. Thanks to all the cross-party support, we're closer than ever to making this change happen."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Jack Brereton",
            "rewritten_speech": "Congrats on this important Bill! 🎉 It's a big deal because it impacts people’s identity and right to be British, which is super important. With our history, it's crucial we move this forward."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Gavin Robinson",
            "rewritten_speech": "Thanks, Jack! 😊 Yep, the goal of this Bill is to fill in a missing piece. Basically, if you were born in the Republic but live here, it should be easy to become a UK citizen. It’s more than just applying normally because our countries have a unique historical connection. This goes way back to 1801, and it changed with Irish independence in 1949. Since then, people like my friend Lord Hay, who was born in Donegal but has been here forever, can't easily get British citizenship. Should someone like him, who's contributed so much, have to pay a huge naturalisation fee or take a citizenship test? 🤔 The Bill doesn't force anyone to become a UK citizen, but opens the door for those who want it. There are about 40,400 folks in Northern Ireland born in the Republic, and this Bill could really matter for around 32,000 of them. Let’s step up and solve this long-running issue already!"
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Fiona Bruce",
            "rewritten_speech": "There's a big issue here that goes beyond Northern Ireland—it's about citizenship and identity for people across the UK 🇬🇧. I totally get why Gav's pushing this Bill. Some folks have grown up feeling British but only have Irish passports because they were born on the other side of an open border. They shouldn't have to go through such a hassle to get British citizenship. Holding a British passport when you identify as British really matters! ✈️ The Bill keeps it limited to those living in Northern Ireland for five years, so it’s not just anyone applying. It's all about fairness. Cheers to Gav for bringing common sense legislation to the table. Let's support it!"
        },
