            "rewritten_speech": "Right, so this new Bill I'm proposing is all about making sure you can connect to any mobile network no matter where you live. We had a good chat about this last Wednesday too—once isn’t enough if it’s worth saying! 😄 The government wants to boost 4G coverage from 91% to 95% by 2025, especially in rural areas. They’re throwing in half a billion pounds for new masts where there’s literally no signal right now. 🎉 But it’s not happening fast enough for folks in spots like Cockshutt or West Felton in my area. Improving rural coverage is super important—not just for business (80% of rural business owners say it's key) but also because when the old landlines go, and power cuts hit, folks need a reliable mobile signal. Elderly people, especially, rely on it. Plus, a reliable mobile connection could prevent digital inequalities and help in emergencies, like agricultural accidents or health issues. But in North Shropshire, only about 60% get indoor coverage, which is super low compared to the 86% UK average. In villages, it’s even worse. Some providers, like EE, have their masts ready, but there's drama about sharing them. So, this Bill steps in to make sure network operators share infrastructure as much as possible. It could even mean rural roaming, which some people worry about, but could work based on past reports. This Bill aims to force a bit of cooperation, and, hopefully, give everyone reliable service wherever they go. 🚀"
