{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Chris Grayling",
            "rewritten_speech": "Hey everyone, I'm here to talk about a big issue with fish supply. We want to make sure the fish you buy isn't from dodgy or unsustainable sources. In the past, we've focused on saving forests, and now we're turning attention to the ocean 🌊. We've done some good stuff like banning bottom trawling (where those nets scrape the ocean floor and mess up marine life), but illegal fishing is still a big issue. 

Some stats for you: Illegal fishing, especially from places like China and Russia, is hurting small coastal communities and wiping out fish stocks. West Africa is suffering from this, with 40% of their fish caught illegally! That's billions of dollars lost and bad news for the environment. 

Although the UK and EU have tight rules, they're not enough. We also learnt when the Ukraine conflict started that loads of our fish, especially white fish, come from Russia. Alongside China, they're the big players in this illegal fishing game. But let’s face it, we can't just rely on regulations alone. We gotta be smart and start tracking the supply chains of fish all the way to the checkout. Like how we've started doing with risky forest products.

The idea is simple: make sure when you're buying fish from supermarkets, they can say for sure it's caught in a good way. Businesses should do their homework (due diligence, if you like). It’s basically about being green and making sure fish stocks in the UK and worldwide are sustainable, and that shady businesses aren't winning. 

I’m super proud that the UK took the lead on forest risk products. Let’s continue and make sure our fishy products are not depleting the oceans elsewhere. By putting this Bill into play, we’re aiming for a better future for our oceans and environment 🌍🦈. 

A shoutout to everyone who's supported this Bill - Chris Grayling, Andrew Selous, Harriett Baldwin, and more. The Bill’s off for its first chat and will be back again in June for round two!"
        }
    ]
}

