{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Alex Chalk",
            "rewritten_speech": "Alright folks, here's the deal on our criminal justice system for England and Wales. We’ve gotta keep people safe, right? That means cutting crime, reducing reoffending, and making sure the baddest of the bad are locked up as long as needed. Good news is, crime's dropped significantly over the last decade. Violent crimes and burglaries down by more than 50% since 2010, and reoffending rates have dropped from 31% to 25%. That's not by chance; it’s thanks to some solid decisions like tagging offenders and giving the police powers they need. We're making sure the serious criminals serve longer sentences. For example, rapists now serve nearly three years more than they did in 2010. We’re also planning to make sure rapists serve their whole term in prison, no early get-out for them. 🤨 Moreover, the worst offenders, like those killing through dangerous driving, are getting lengthier sentences, and we’ve got new rules letting the Secretary of State stop the release of those who are a risk, like Robert Brown.🤚 At the same time, we’re expanding prisons! We’re making 10,000 more prison spaces by 2025 and aiming for 20,000 overall. Today, I want to talk about foreign national offenders (FNOs). We've got about 10,500 of them, which costs us around £47,000 per prisoner yearly. That's quite a strain on our resources, huh? We’re working hard to send these lawbreakers back to their countries; 4,000 were sent back last year, a 27% increase from the previous year. We've extended a scheme allowing us to deport eligible FNOs up to six months earlier. Also, we have a new agreement with Albania for sending their offenders back. And yes, we’re also looking to rent prisons overseas like some European countries do! We’re setting up a taskforce and adding 400 caseworkers to process these FNOs faster. Plus, we’re using diplomatic channels to make deportation deals with countries like Italy. And we’re ready to use our new powers under the Nationality and Borders Act to restrict visas from countries unhelpful in FNO removals. So that's the plan, and next year we aim to deport more than double the offenders than last year! 😤 On remand population, things got a bit tight since the pandemic. We could have released loads of prisoners due to Covid, as some countries did, but we didn’t, which was the right move. We also resisted calls to change jury trials during Covid. Now, with more people awaiting trial, we’re exploring remote bail hearings, adding more caseworkers, investing in a bail information service, and expanding accommodation with additional £22 million funding. All probation services need to be on top form to make this work, and we're investing in them, too – £155 million a year and loads of new trainees. The goal is to focus efforts where they make the biggest impact. 🙌 Thanks to everyone working in our justice system! We are committed to doing whatever it takes to keep Britain safe."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Shabana Mahmood",
            "rewritten_speech": "Thanks for the heads-up on the statement, Mr. Secretary. But releasing prisoners up to two months early to make space in jails is causing a stir—and rightly so! The announcement came out sneakily last night, but people deserve clarity. This is a massive change, the biggest early release scheme we’ve seen, and it's very concerning. But only one puny paragraph in your whole statement about it? 😮 People who broke the law are getting out early – possibly a threat to law-abiding folks! This needs more transparency. When this scheme was announced, you said it was temporary, yet it seems it’s being stretched without clear limits. I have questions: How many have been released? Which prisons are doing this? What kind of offenders are getting out early? Are stalkers and domestic abusers included? Why stretch it to 60 days and indefinitely? We need to see weekly data on this, not yearly after the next election! You did mention more pressure on the probation service with these releases. But what’s the ‘reset’ you suggested? There’s no extra money for probation to handle this. Rushing such measures increases public risk. Be honest, please—admit the risks. How will you ensure probation services can assess risks properly? Any risk assessment done? How do you make sure inexperienced probation staff aren’t overwhelmed? You claim progress on deporting FNOs, but it's far behind what was done in 2010 under Labour. Foreign offenders still living freely after release, so let’s double staffing as a credible plan, instead of just four hundred new officers. This is a huge change to the system, and the public deserves proper answers."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Alex Chalk",
            "rewritten_speech": "Shabana raised some important issues, but there’s no mention of Labour's own release scheme which ran for three years. Risk is rightly a concern, but let’s break it down rationally. Unlike Labour’s old scheme with no conditions, our scheme has strict licence conditions. Labour’s version let all prisons apply it; ours is selective. Plus, if a governor's got safety concerns about someone’s release, a panel steps in to assess—before overlooking that, under Labour, no safety check was there! Safety first is our motto. On overcrowding, it's true we faced tough decisions during Covid like releasing loads of prisoners. Yet, unlike other nations that released thousands, we didn’t, prioritising public safety. Skipping jury trials would have clogged the system longer; hence more inmates now. Yet, we insist on justice over shortcuts. Opposition needs to address these questions because, truthfully, these measures are defensible. Playing politics like this won’t do anyone any good."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Bob Neill",
            "rewritten_speech": "Alex, your approach makes sense. Oversimplifying things isn’t helpful. Managing our prison capacity is complex, and you're right—this requires careful checks and balances. Given that prison space is limited and costly, it’s logical to lock up truly dangerous people and look at smart alternatives for less serious offenders. Is this not what we’re aiming for?"
        },
