{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Tonia Antoniazzi",
            "rewritten_speech": "Hey everyone, I've got a new Bill I want to talk about. It's all about making sure that police officers and some police employees tell us if they're part of certain clubs or groups. Think about those secret societies we've often joked about with funny handshakes – they're not just a laugh, they can be pretty powerful networks! In the UK, policing is about trust and fairness, right? So, we need transparency in our police forces. A recent report from the Casey Report really hit home how crucial checks and transparency are. 😇 

This Bill will push for a public register where officers and police staff disclose memberships. It's not a new idea either! Back in '97, there was talk about needing a register for secret societies like Freemasons, and the Home Office even agreed with it the following year! There's always been chatter about the influence of Freemasons in policing – no accusations here, but it gets people curious. 🤔 

But my Bill isn't just about Freemasons. It's about any group that acts like an exclusive club, which can be found in police culture. We've been hearing tons about issues like racism and corruption in the police. For real reform, we can't leave any stone unturned, my friends. And let's be clear, I'm not saying folks can't join societies. Freedom to associate is a thing, after all. 

This isn't about party politics – it's about making the police fair and transparent. I've had a right old chat with loads of folks, and many agree we need to do something though not everyone is bold enough to speak up. I've done similar stuff with the Welsh Rugby Union before, so I know that saying something can spur real change. The idea is to balance police duties with transparency, making sure the public doesn't lose trust in them. 

Many of us, like teachers, already have to do these DBS checks, which is similar, isn't it? Some say politicians too should declare their memberships, and I'm all, 'yeah, why not?' It might remind you of the Welsh Assembly days when members had to declare being Freemasons or else face serious consequences. Now, they must declare any society memberships. It's smart and fair if you ask me. 

Being part of clubs can be ace, building friendships and doing good, but not when they're used to hide wrongdoings. We've got our work cut out to build trust in our police, and this Bill is just one step. Transparency is key! Remember, the 1998 report said the solution was straightforward: no bans, just transparency. It's time to ditch the secrecy game, my mates! 

So, we're presenting the Bill, thanks to my awesome colleagues from different parties who back this! 😊 Let's bring about some positive change!"
        }
    ]
}

