        {
            "speakername": "Clive Betts",
            "rewritten_speech": "So, folks, our committee just dropped a report on 'Financial distress in local authorities,' and it's a bit alarming. First, quick shout-out to the Leader of the House for making this statement happen. Our committee clerk is thrilled because apparently we've set a new procedural record today, which is news to me, but hey! 😄\n\nThis report digs into the financial black hole that local councils are facing, especially when it comes to stuff like social care, education needs, and homelessness. We're trying to sound the alarm before the next financial settlement for local governments. Basically, councils are in a bind because they're spending more than they earn, and that wasn't always the case. In the last couple of decades, we had only eight councils in this predicament, but that's ballooned recently. And it's not just a few councils; it's happening everywhere! 😱\n\nThe big bad here is a massive funding gap worth billions. Council income just isn't keeping pace with rising service demands and inflation. In short, the current funding system is a mess, and successive governments cutting central grants isn't helping. Council tax has gone up 20%, but, overall, there's been an almost 26% drop in spending power since 2010.\n\nImmediate funding is a must. While the government announced £600 million more funding recently, it's not enough. Our report has some ideas on better funding reforms in the medium term, like giving councils more flexibility over how they spend.\n\nThe rise in costs mainly comes from adult and children’s social care, education needs, and homelessness. We’re pushing for funding increases and systematic overhauls across the board. On a lighter long-term note, increasing social housing could help with homelessness rather than just chucking money at temporary fixes.\n\nWe need whoever is in charge next to get serious about reforming local funding and taxes. Council tax and business rates need clarity and fairness. We suggest exploring options like different kinds of taxes or fiscal changes to really sort this mess out for good. Fingers crossed our recommendations make the financial debates next week, and future administrations give them the thought they deserve."
