{
    "speeches": [
        {
            "speakername": "Thomas Tugendhat",
            "rewritten_speech": "Hey everyone, I'm going to chat about the new steps we're taking to deal with bad behaviours during protests. After those terrible events on 7th October, many folks went out to show their opinions. A lot did it peacefully, and I had the honour of walking with many, including some from this House, against antisemitism in Manchester and London. But sadly, that's not the full picture. Lately, we've seen some really nasty incidents of hate, and people being stopped from living their everyday lives. Yes, protesting is crucial in our democracy, but nasty stuff like throwing racist slurs, vandalising memorials, or intimidating with flares is just not on. We're putting a stop to this through new steps, like banning the use of protest as an excuse for criminal behaviour. If protesters are blocking roads or interfering with ambulances, their excuses won't wash anymore. People in the UK want a peaceful life without such disruptions. \n \nWe're also drafting measures against folks defacing war memorials, and those who hide their faces to avoid justice during protests. Flares will be banned—if you're caught with them, you'll face serious consequences, including a fine or a short stint in jail. We brought in new laws a year ago to help police handle protests better, and since then, the police have made over 600 arrests to keep protests from getting out of hand. We owe a big thanks to our officers for their hard work in keeping us safe. Freedom of speech is key, but not when it crosses into violence or intimidation. We've even banned certain groups who promote terror. We'll keep working hard to protect our communities and maintain order."
        },
        {
            "speakername": "Dan Jarvis",
            "rewritten_speech": "Thanks to the Minister for the update. Labour absolutely backs the right to peaceful protest, but when things get out of hand, we need to protect the public. Police have to balance keeping order and allowing protests, so we'll look closely at these new plans to make sure they're sensible and fair. \n \nAs for the measures mentioned: first, there's a plan to arrest those covering their faces to hide at protests. We get why, but sometimes covering up is for safety—like when dissidents protest against foreign embassies, for family protection back home. How will this be fairly applied?\n \nNext, banning flares is sensible since they've caused chaos before. Big protests are tricky, so how will police deal with that? Third, on war memorials—everyone agrees they need respect. There's outrage when they're desecrated, and justly so. But there's still confusion on what defines 'hate extremism', so when's the Government going to clear that up and update their strategy? \n \nProtesting is a key freedom, provided it's not abused; and we shouldn't clamp down unless it's necessary. Labour will dig into these proposals to ensure they balance protest rights and public safety."
        },
